^ That's an example worker without Hono or Typescript. Source code, if you want to copy/paste it into the CF Workers editor:

<details>

```js
class StreamingApi {
  constructor(writable) {
    this.bytesWritten = 0;
    this.writer = writable.getWriter();
    this.encoder = new TextEncoder();
  }

  write(str) {
    const bytes = this.encoder.encode(str);
    this.bytesWritten += bytes.length;
    this.writer.write(bytes);
    return this;
  }

  writeln(str) {
    return this.write(str + "\n");
  }

  flush() {
    const bytes_needed = 4096 - (this.bytesWritten % 4096);
    const BACKSPACE = 8;
    this.writer.write(new Uint8Array(bytes_needed).fill(BACKSPACE));
    this.bytesWritten = 0;
  }

  close() {
    this.writer.close();
  }
}

const textStream = (cb) => {
  const { readable, writable } = new TransformStream();
  const stream = new StreamingApi(writable);
  cb(stream).finally(() => stream.close());
  return new Response(readable, {
    headers: {
      "content-type": "text/plain",
      "Transfer-Encoding": "chunked",
    },
  });
};

export default {
  async fetch(request, env) {
    return textStream(async (stream) => {
      for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        console.log(i);
        stream.writeln(i).flush();
        await new Promise((res) => setTimeout(res, 1000));
      }
    });
  }
}
```

</details>

### How does it work?

To do this kind of chunked-streaming from CF Workers, you need a couple of things:

* To create a `ReadableStream` and `WritableStream` using `new TransformStream()`
* Return a `Response` with the `readable` as the body, and `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` header.
* Use `writable.write()` to push content onto the stream
* ðŸš¨ **DANK HAX ALERT** ðŸš¨ Pad out chunks to the nearest 4096 bytes so CF sends them immediately, otherwise they're buffered (thx [this post](https://community.cloudflare.com/t/streaming-responses/106683/4)). I send `ASCII 8 (BACKSPACE)` because cURL ignores this.
* Remember to `writable.close()` to end the stream & close the response.
* Hit it with cURL, potentially with `-N` flag. Browsers don't seem to stream things correctly, and also the backspaces make Chrome download it as a file and Firefox displays them as little hex chars. But curl works great.

I've made a `textStream` function that gives this API:

```ts
return textStream(async (stream) => {
  for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    stream.writeln(i).flush();
    await new Promise((res) => setTimeout(res, 1000));
  }
});
```

It sets up the TransformStream invokes the callback (without awaiting it) and returns the Response:

```ts
type TextStream = (cb: (stream: StreamingApi) => Promise<void>) => Response;
const textStream: TextStream = (cb) => {
  const { readable, writable } = new TransformStream();
  const stream = new StreamingApi(writable);
  cb(stream).finally(() => stream.close());
  return new Response(readable, {
    headers: {
      "content-type": "text/plain",
      "Transfer-Encoding": "chunked",
    },
  });
};
```

The `stream` property that's passed into the callback is an instance of this `StreamingApi` class, which provides helpers like `.write`, `.writeln`, `.flush` etc. This could be expanded with a bunch of helpers, but here is the implementation as-is:

```ts
class StreamingApi {
  private bytesWritten: number;
  private writer: WritableStreamDefaultWriter;
  private encoder: TextEncoder;

  constructor(writable: WritableStream) {
    this.bytesWritten = 0;
    this.writer = writable.getWriter();
    this.encoder = new TextEncoder();
  }

  write(str) {
    const bytes = this.encoder.encode(str);
    this.bytesWritten += bytes.length;
    this.writer.write(bytes);
    return this;
  }

  writeln(str) {
    return this.write(str + "\n");
  }

  flush() {
    const bytes_needed = 4096 - (this.bytesWritten % 4096);
    const BACKSPACE = 8;
    this.writer.write(new Uint8Array(bytes_needed).fill(BACKSPACE));
    this.bytesWritten = 0;
  }

  close() {
    this.writer.close();
