This is an issue related to routers.

The results when handling routes such as `/:id/*` vary between each router. If you have the following app:

```ts
app.get('/:id/*', (c) => {
  return c.text(`${c.req.param('id')}`)
})
```

What are the results when accessing `/`, `/foo`, and `/foo/bar`? The results are as follows:

```
GET /
TrieRouter: 404
RegExpRouter: 404
LinearRouter: Error
PatternRouter: 404

GET /foo
TrieRouter: 404
RegExpRouter: 200 foo
LinearRouter: Error
PatternRouter: 200 undefined

GET /foo/bar
TrieRouter: 200 foo
RegExpRouter: 200 foo
LinearRouter: Error
PatternRouter: 200 undefined
```

These are not expected. Therefore, we need to decide on the behavior for `/:id/*` and fix the implementation.

I believe we should follow the specification used by *TrieRouter*, which would result in:

```
GET / => 404
GET /foo => 404
GET /foo/bar => 200 foo
```

If we choose this specification, the routes that need fixing are:

*RegExpRouter*
* GET /foo

*PatternRouter*
* GET /foo
* GET /foo/bar

*LinearRouter* throws `UnsupportedPathError` errors for all patterns. If we allow this, we will need to use it with the *SmartRouter* and *TrieRouter* for the preset `hono/quick`.

This is an edge case, but we must resolve it as issues like #1240 have been raised.

### The script

```ts
import { Hono } from 'hono'
import { type Router } from 'hono/dist/types/router'
import { LinearRouter } from 'hono/router/linear-router'
import { PatternRouter } from 'hono/router/pattern-router'
import { RegExpRouter } from 'hono/router/reg-exp-router'
import { TrieRouter } from 'hono/router/trie-router'

const createHono = (router: Router<any>) => {
  const app = new Hono({
    router: router,
  })
  app.get('/:id/*', (c) => {
    return c.text(`${c.req.param('id')}`)
  })
  app.showRoutes()
  return app
}

const routers: Router<any>[] = [
  new TrieRouter(),
  new RegExpRouter(),
  new LinearRouter(),
  new PatternRouter(),
]

const apps: Record<string, Hono> = {}

for (const router of routers) {
  const app = createHono(router)
  apps[router.name] = app
}

const request = async (path: string) => {
  console.log(`GET ${path}`)
  for (const [name, app] of Object.entries(apps)) {
    try {
      const res = await app.request(path)
      if (res.ok) {
        console.log(`${name}: ${res.status} ${await res.text()}`)
      } else {
        console.log(`${name}: ${res.status}`)
      }
    } catch (e) {
      console.log(`${name}: Error`)
    }
  }
}

console.log('')
await request('/')
console.log('')
await request('/foo')
console.log('')
await request('/foo/bar')
```

Hello, 

I just wanted to point that right now hono doesn't support advance mode with cloudflare pages. As you can see in advance mode the signature of function is a bit different so the existing handle function from `hono/cloudflare-pages` won't work here. 

https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/platform/functions/advanced-mode/#set-up-a-function

```
export default {
  async fetch(request, env) {
    const url = new URL(request.url);
    if (url.pathname.startsWith('/api/')) {
      // TODO: Add your custom /api/* logic here.
      return new Response('Ok');
    }
    // Otherwise, serve the static assets.
    // Without this, the Worker will error and no assets will be served.
    return env.ASSETS.fetch(request);
  },
}
```

As discussed in #1243, the LinearRouter can't handle all route patterns. Therefore, the `hono/quick` preset must use SmartRouter with LinearRouter and TrieRouter.

```ts
this.router = new SmartRouter({
  routers: [new LinearRouter(), new TrieRouter()],
})
```

