### Support `Suspense` in non-streaming mode.

`Suspense` can also be used in a non-streaming configuration. In this case, the output HTML does not contain any JavaScript, but is the text that has been replaced.

However, now that async components are available in Hono, this feature has no particular advantage. It may be useful for users who are used to "throw a Promise in `Suspense`".

```tsx
const app = new Hono()

let shop
function Shop({ id }) {
  if (!shop) {
    throw fetch(`https://ramen-api.dev/shops/${id}`).then((res) => res.json()).then((data) => shop = data.shop)
  }
  return <div>{shop.name}</div>
}

app.get('/suspense-non-streaming', async (c) => {
  return c.html(
    <html>
      <body>
        <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
          <Shop id="takasagoya" />
        </Suspense>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
})
```

### Introduce `ErrorBoundary` component.

This is more of a main issue, adding an ErrorBoundary that can be replaced by a fallback when an error occurs in the processing of children.
This is true for synchronous rendering, asynchronous rendering including async, and streaming, all of which produce the same expected results in all environments.

https://github.com/honojs/hono/assets/30598/72d21b6d-01ef-4d92-96c2-2f6b61af3219

```tsx
const app = new Hono()

async function Shop({ id }) {
  const data = await fetch(`https://ramen-api.dev/shops/${id}`).then((res) => res.json())
  return <div>{data.shop.name}</div>
}

function SyncError() {
  throw new Error('Error')
}

async function AsyncError() {
  await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, 2000))
  throw new Error('Error')
}

function Fallback() {
  return <div>Out Of Service</div>
}

app.get('/sync', async (c) => {
  return c.html(
    <html>
      <body>
        <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
          <SyncError />
        </ErrorBoundary>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
})

app.get('/async', async (c) => {
  return c.html(
    <html>
      <body>
        <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
          <Shop id='takasagoya' />
        </ErrorBoundary>
        <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
          <AsyncError />
        </ErrorBoundary>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
})

app.get('/streaming-suspense-all', async (c) => {
  return c.body(
    renderToReadableStream(
      <html>
        <body>
          <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <Shop id='takasagoya' />
            </Suspense>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <Shop id='sugitaya' />
            </Suspense>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <AsyncError />
            </Suspense>
          </ErrorBoundary>
        </body>
      </html>
    ),
    {
      headers: {
        'Transfer-Encoding': 'chunked',
        'Content-Type': 'text/html; charset=UTF-8',
      },
    }
  )
})

app.get('/streaming-suspense-each', async (c) => {
  return c.body(
    renderToReadableStream(
      <html>
        <body>
          <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <Shop id='takasagoya' />
            </Suspense>
          </ErrorBoundary>
          <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <Shop id='sugitaya' />
            </Suspense>
          </ErrorBoundary>
          <ErrorBoundary fallback={<Fallback />}>
            <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
              <AsyncError />
            </Suspense>
          </ErrorBoundary>
        </body>
      </html>
    ),
    {
      headers: {
        'Transfer-Encoding': 'chunked',
        'Content-Type': 'text/html; charset=UTF-8',
      },
    }
  )
})
```

### Is this a necessary feature for Hono?

A component named ErrorBoundary is introduced in the official React documentation, but it is not provided complete and is to be created by the user as needed. However, there seems to be an OSS that is very widely used.

https://react.dev/reference/react/Component
https://github.com/bvaughn/react-error-boundary

Personally, I would prefer to refrain from original extensions that are not in the original React, but on the other hand, I think that `ErrorBoundary` is useful enough and worth providing officially, as it would be difficult for users to implement it by themselves.




